l public class in the same file. It seems I can’t. Perhaps I could make a public `FactoryFinderTest` that extends `RuntimeDelegate`? This way, the system property could refer to the test class itself. The test class must have a no-argument public constructor and can contain `@Test` methods, which is a smart solution!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Class instantiation**\\n\\nI’m considering if `Class.newInstance` can work in native if the class is registered for reflection and its constructor metadata is available. If the constructor is directly reachable, then it might be \\\"unsafeAllocated,\\\" suggesting I likely need reflection config. I should add a `META-INF/native-image/reachability-metadata.json` file with reflection entries for the `FactoryFinderTest` constructor. Also, resources may not be necessary unless used for dynamic access. I'm exploring how the class loader works and ensuring I handle the system properties correctly for class instantiation!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering system properties and implementation**\\n\\nI need to restore the original system property while being cautious with `getInstance`, as it caches values. It's essential to reset things before and after without using direct reflection in tests. I wonder if I should stick with `Class<?>` to avoid reflection. Using `class.getName` or class literals seems fine. I’ll implement the abstract methods minimally and consider throwing `UnsupportedOperationException` for unused ones. I'll also need to import several classes like `Application`, `ResponseBuilder`, and others since my class extends `RuntimeDelegate`. Should I include AssertJ for assertions too?\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_SVrkrLxZHGxigCXiF12oZOBp|fc_0364aeba562348450169f10d84ffd08195a7b1e55c439f2f01", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/javax.ws.rs/jsr311-api/1.1.1/src/test/java/javax_ws_rs/jsr311_api/FactoryFinderTest.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and